</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-31_ pf-text-1">A study by Skills for Care revealed that around 36% of adult social care staff leave their roles every year, emphasising the need for ongoing training and support to retain skilled workers.























































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-33_ pf-text-1">Research by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) indicates that properly trained support workers can enhance patient outcomes, reduce hospital readmissions, and improve service users' overall quality of life.


























































</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-35_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-36_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-37_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions
</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-39_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Support workers, also known as healthcare assistants or care assistants, provide practical and emotional support to individuals who require assistance with daily living activities due to illness, disability, or age-related conditions. Their duties may include personal care, medication administration, meal preparation, and companionship.





 

  
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-41_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-42_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3">Relevant legislation, regulations, and best practice</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-45_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-46_ pf-text-1">The Care Quality Commission (CQC) sets standards for the quality and safety of care services in England. Care providers must comply with CQC regulations, including support worker training standards.












































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-48_ pf-text-1">The Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 and the Management of Health and Safety at Work Regulations 1999 outline employers' legal obligations to ensure their staff's health, safety, and well-being, including support workers.
























































</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-50_ pf-text-1">Best practice guidelines from professional bodies such as the Royal College of Nursing (RCN) and the British Association of Social Workers (BASW) provide valuable insights into effective support worker training strategies. They emphasise the importance of continuous professional development (CPD) and person-centred care approaches.

























































</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-52_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-53_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-54_ pf-heading-1-h3">Understanding the support worker role</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-56_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Support workers are pivotal in delivering high-quality care across various healthcare and social care settings. Their responsibilities encompass a wide range of tasks to support individuals to live as independently as possible while maintaining their dignity and autonomy.






 

  
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-58_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-59_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-60_ pf-heading-1-h3">The importance of training and development</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-62_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Effective support worker training goes beyond basic competency assessments. It equips individuals with the necessary knowledge, skills, and attitudes to deliver person-centred care tailored to the unique needs of each service user. Continuous professional development ensures support workers stay abreast of best practices, emerging trends, and evolving regulatory requirements.







 

  
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-64_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-65_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-66_ pf-heading-1-h3">Legislation and regulation compliance</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-68_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Adhering to legislative and regulatory frameworks is non-negotiable in providing care services. Support worker training programmes must align with statutory requirements and regulatory standards to ensure safe, effective, and compassionate care delivery.








 

  
